Partial pooling

Dr R. Morris, School of Psychology, University of Sydney

Sep 14, 2022

library(tidyverse)
library(brms)

We will estimate average trial accuracy using logistic regression, in a random intercept model with a varying intercept for each person.

The amount of shrinkage is a function of the relative variance/precision of the group (j) estimates:

$$ \[\begin{align} \hat U_j &= \rho_j \bar y_j + (1 - \rho_j) \bar y \\ \\ \text{where} \\ \rho_j &= \frac{\tau^2}{(\tau^2 + \sigma^2 / n_j)} \end{align}\] $$

Michael Clarke has an excellent blogpost on shrinkage in random effect models (random intercept + random slope).

Other good resources are Solomon Kurzs adaptation of Richard McElreaths Statistical Rethinking.


The model

The simulation model of trial accuracy \(i\) for each person \(j = 1...60\):

$$ \[\begin{align} response_i &\sim Binomial(n_i, \ p_i) \\ logit(p_i) &= \alpha_{j[i]} &\text{unique accuracy for each person}\\ \alpha_j &\sim Normal(\bar \alpha, \ \sigma) &\text{adaptive prior for j = 1...60}\\ \\ \bar \alpha &\sim Normal(0, \ 1.5) &\text{prior for average person}\\ \sigma &\sim Exponential(1) &\text{prior for sd of persons}\\ \end{align}\] $$


Assign values to the parameters

Parameters for the population mean (a_bar) and sd (sigma) can be set here. The simulation parameters are shown in the table below, along with a plot of the true values from which the data will be simulated.

a_bar     <- 1.5 # average (log) accuracy for the population
sigma_lo  <- 1 # standard deviation of accuracy in the population
sigma_hi  <- 3
n_persons <- 60
n_trial   <- rep(c(5, 10, 25, 35), each = n_persons / 4) %>% as.integer() # trials per person

set.seed(1)
alpha_lo  <- rnorm(n = n_persons, mean = a_bar, sd = sigma_lo) # accuracy per person
alpha_hi  <- rnorm(n = n_persons, mean = a_bar, sd = sigma_hi) # accuracy per person

sim_lo <- tibble(
  person = 1:n_persons,
  block_size = n_trial,
  true_alpha = alpha_lo) %>%
  mutate(
    true_p = inv_logit_scaled(true_alpha),
    true_sigma = as.character(sigma_lo))

sim_hi <- tibble(
  person = 1:n_persons,
  block_size = n_trial,
  true_alpha = alpha_hi) %>%
  mutate(
    true_p = inv_logit_scaled(true_alpha),
    true_sigma = as.character(sigma_hi))


Figure 1.


Simulate correct responses

Each person has \(n_i\) potential correct responses, and so the probablity of a correct response for each person is \(p_i\). The probability \(p_i\) implied by the model definition is:

\[ p_i = \frac{exp(\alpha_i)}{1 + exp(\alpha_i)} \]

A binomial draw from the true parameters gives us the observed (simulated) number of correct trials for each person.

set.seed(1)
dsim <- dsim %>%
  mutate(correct = rbinom(n = n(), 
                       prob = true_p, 
                       size = block_size))


No pooling estimates

Obtaining the unpooled estimates in this context is simply the calculated probability of a correct response for each person:

dsim <- dsim %>%
  mutate(p_nopool = correct / block_size,
         person = as.character(person))


The no_pool estimates are the same as those obtained from a glm, e.g.:

dsim %>%
   mutate(incorrect = block_size - correct) %>%
   glm(cbind(correct, incorrect) ~ 0 + factor(person),
       family = "binomial",
       data = .) %>%
   broom::tidy() %>%
   mutate(p_nopool = inv_logit_scaled(estimate))


Partial pooling estimates

Partially-pooled estimates can be obtained from brms or lme4.

The syntax of this aggregated binomial model will be slightly different in each case. brms uses trials() notation on the LHS to indicate the denominator for each (aggregated) count of correct responses.

fit_lo <- brm(data = filter(dsim, true_sigma==as.character(sigma_lo)), 
                family = binomial,
                correct | trials(block_size) ~ 1 + (1 | person),
                prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1.5), class = Intercept),
                          prior(exponential(.10), class = sd)),
                iter = 5000, chains = 4, cores = 4,
                file = paste0(home, "docs/fit_lo.rds"),
                seed = 1)

fit_hi <- brm(data = filter(dsim, true_sigma==as.character(sigma_hi)), 
                family = binomial,
                correct | trials(block_size) ~ 1 + (1 | person),
                prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1.5), class = Intercept),
                          prior(exponential(.10), class = sd)),
                iter = 5000, chains = 4, cores = 4,
                file = paste0(home, "docs/fit_hi.rds"),
                seed = 1)
library(lme4)
glmer.fit <- glmer(data = dsim, 
                   family = "binomial",
                   formula = cbind(correct, block_size - correct) ~ 1 + (1 | person)
                   # formula = correct / block_size ~ 1 + (1 | person),
                   # weights = block_size
)

After fitting, we extract the conditional estimates (partially-pooled) for each person. The conditional estimates are simply the random estimates + fixed estimates.

# conditional effects for each person
p_partpool <- coef(fit_lo)$person[, , ] %>% 
  as_tibble(rownames = "person") %>%
  mutate(
    true_sigma = as.character(sigma_lo),
    p_est = inv_logit_scaled(Estimate)      # brms conditional effects
    ) %>%
  bind_rows(
    coef(fit_hi)$person[, , ] %>% 
      as_tibble(rownames = "person") %>%
      mutate(
        true_sigma = as.character(sigma_hi),
        p_est = inv_logit_scaled(Estimate) # lme4 conditional effects
        )
    )

# fixed effect (population)
p_fixed <- bind_rows(
  posterior_summary(fit_lo, variable = "b_Intercept", robust=T) %>%
    as_tibble() %>%
    mutate(true_sigma = as.character(sigma_lo)),
  posterior_summary(fit_hi, variable = "b_Intercept", robust=T) %>%
    as_tibble() %>%
    mutate(true_sigma = as.character(sigma_hi))
) %>%
  mutate(across(c(Estimate, Q2.5, Q97.5), inv_logit_scaled))


Comparing estimates


Figure 2.
## Joining, by = c("person", "true_sigma")
## Joining, by = "true_sigma"

Key points

  • The conditional estimates are generally shifted towards the fixed effect relative to the unpooled estimates (shrinkage)
  • Less shrinkage occurs with larger \(n_j\)
  • More shrinkage occurs as the estimate is further from the fixed effect
  • Less shrinkage occurs as the variance between groups increases (true_alpha)


Assessing estimates

Calculating the difference between each estimate and the true accuracy rate for each person (\(\alpha_j\)) can tell us which model is better representing the data generating process. Not surprisingly in a multilevel DGP, a multilevel model produces estimates closer to the true parameters from which the data was simulated.

data_to_plot <- dsim %>%
  left_join(p_partpool) %>%
  mutate(nopool_error   = abs(p_nopool  - true_p),
         partpool_error = abs(p_est - true_p)) %>%
  select(person, true_sigma, block_size, nopool_error, partpool_error) %>%
  gather("name", "value", nopool_error:partpool_error)
## Joining, by = c("person", "true_sigma")


Figure 3.

Key points

  • Error decreases as group size increases
  • Partial pooling produces better estimates when true alpha is small
